**Q. Are there any risks identified for the Shopping Ads launch?**
 There are external and internal risks associated with the launch of Shopping Ads. Externally, we do not meet Google’s standard for enabling Shopping Ads and will need to pursue an exception to launch. The likelihood of this exception being approved is dependent on how far from their standards we are with our launched CX. From initial conversations with Google, we do not believe we will receive an exception until we can 1) show a differentiated shopping experience (Business branded) for all customer and prospect traffic (existing consumers, existing businesses, unrecognized traffic), 2) allow all customers to make a purchase at the advertised price, and 3) do not allow verification holds to prevent orders. With these restrictions, we believe the fastest we could enable Shopping Ads is Milestone 3 where all traffic can see the shopping experience, and we will need to advertise with a B2C price externally. To enable B2B pricing externally, we will need to allow for that advertised price to be purchasable by all traffic regardless of verification state – (Project Aladin ETA TBD). By displaying B2c pricing externally, we prevent price perception risk for Amazon Consumer since customers on Google won’t see the same product sold by Amazon at two different prices where we cannot limit the experience to business customers. When customers display business intent by clicking on the AB Branded ad, they will see business prices alongside the advertised Consumer price, enabling opportunity for prospect self-selection between experiences and further safeguarding against cannibalization. This approach also safeguards AB against potential vendor/seller pushback where business prices would be otherwise advertised externally to non-verified accounts.
Internally, we will be required to work within existing central team price and offer feeds to Google due to Google only allowing one shopping feed per domain. We are requesting away team support through OP1 and allocating internal resourcing to make this feed multi-tenant, however this will require significant alignment and potentially funding or tech swaps with the consumer team. We aligned in 2024 with L7 leaders that this is a good opportunity for Amazon as a whole, however due to recent team turnover we will need to revisit the topic between OP1 and OP2 and secure another shared goal with AME. Without alignment internally, we would need to pursue an exception with Google to be treated differently from consumer, a task AWS was successful in doing but was not easily received. Operationally, Shopping Ads will be a significant increase in the amount of campaigns and budget, and presents unique management and optimization approach vs current Paid Search ads. We will reduce required resources through build of automation tools, including ATL work with Generative to use ML and intelligence to assist the Marketing team in the creation, management, and optimization of Text and Shopping Ads. However, this is an unproven tool. We are investing time in Q3/Q4 2025 to validate the potential for Generative AI for a higher confidence launch of Shopping Ads in 2026.
