OCI (Offline Conversion Import) is an Amazon-created solution to enable Google bidding, which is strategically critical because it leverages Google's unique ability to understand user intent. While traditional search advertising is limited to targeting based solely on keywords, Google bidding can incorporate signals from across Google's properties (Search, Maps, News feeds, YouTube, etc.) to better understand browsing behavior and interests to drive more accurate bidding decisions. For example, this allows us to differentiate bids between casual shoppers and business-intent buyers searching for the same term, such as “shipping supplies.” OCI acts as a transmission methodology to provide Google with signals representing the *value* of a prospect click while supporting customer and performance privacy - creating a continuous feedback loop where these value signals inform Google’s bidding and targeting decisions, and subsequent performance data confirms and refines those decisions over time. 

Once OCI is available, application of Google bidding consists of 2 steps; a learning phase, where Google calibrates against our Value (4 weeks), and application, where we enable Google Bidding across campaigns. Our application strategy balances speed to market with appropriate risk mitigation and measurement integrity. Aligning to the Consumer approach, we have split our Google Bidding application using a phased roll-out plan. Initially rollout will focus on NonBrand due to higher expected impact and use similarly performing campaigns as Test (Google Bidding applied) and Control (no bidding change). This will allow time-based analysis (pre/post, YoY) as well as analysis between comparative campaigns. Initial phasing will use a 4 week duration as the first 2 weeks are introduce high volatility while Google adjusts bids to identify the right bidding level and search targets.

