1.    What are our hotly debated topics? Note - this was removed in Final

We debate whether we should leverage Amazon’s B2C Associates program or leverage work performed by other Amazon businesses (e.g., Amazon Music, Amazon Photo, Wondery) who have built successful, standalone programs. B2C Associates already supports AB and is actively driving affiliate referrals. This model would not cost additional funding, but would require headcount (HC). Due to existing integration, the pro of choosing this option is that business development resources can immediately focus on driving impact through expanding affiliate partnerships. However there are a few cons. First, further integration being needed for spend engagement as we are not currently tracking or providing commissions to Associates who drive sales on AB. Second, B2C Associates’ tool limits AB’s brand visibility or means for AB to interact directly and exclusively with Associates (See Appendix 2). Third, B2C Associates is a closed system, which prohibits 3P (agency) management of the program. Fourth, since B2C requires funded full-time employee headcount (HC), this route would result in higher headcount requirements. Fifth, given the prioritization of B2C growth, other Amazon orgs have had challenges optimizing for their use cases. Alternatively, we evaluated a Standalone Program. This would cost $X (tech setup cost: $100K, agency/contractors: $X). The pros of this option include the ability to create an AB-only focused interface to support affiliates. Given AB affiliates will largely be differentiated from those supporting B2C (due to their B2B focus). Additionally, having dedicated and fully focused resources allowed Amazon Music, Amazon Photo, and Wondery to launch and optimize quickly using two-way door decisions. Finally, HC commitment can be agency or contractor-based, which provides more flexibility in long-term resource usage. However this option also has cons, including development support to setup the Tech stack (estimated: 3-4 months) and enablement of acquisition and engagement tracking. After evaluating the two options, we recommend moving forward with X due to X.



* ****What other options did we explore to launch an affiliate marketing program?****

Other Amazon businesses (e.g., Amazon Music, Amazon Photo, Wondery) have built successful, standalone programs, outside of B2C Associates. A standalone option allows the ability to create an AB-only focused interface to support affiliates, but requires tech setup and cost (est. 3-4mo setup, $100k ann. cost) to support both acquisition and engagement tracking. This approach allows agency or contractor-based support driving flexibility in resource usage and further enables direct AB oversight of teams (vs Centrally embedded FTE). However, after evaluating a standalone program vs. B2C Associates expansion, we are biasing toward quick activation and leveraging Amazon-owned technology. The reduced tech effort to use B2C Associates will allow us to launch faster and lean on processes and best practices from B2C Associates. 

