## Consumer OCI Performance [AMZ Confidential]

#### **🚀 Search Marketing launches new value-based optimization for US 🚀 [Amazon Confidential]

 What has been launched? **

Search Marketing launched "Offline Conversion Import" (OCI) for US Google, achieving a 25.8% lift in net CCP during A/B testing, with additional optimizations planned. OCI is a next generation Machine Learning based bidding system that utilizes obfuscated conversion signals along with exclusive signals available only to ad-networks in a privacy compliant fashion. This new bidding system is slated to replace existing ML based bidders. OCI leverages thousands of customer-level features available to ad-networks such as location (e.g., the customer searched in Seattle), time (e.g., the customer searched at noon), device/browser, demography (e.g., gender, age, etc.), prior search history, and so on. By enabling our marketing to benefit from these customer level features, we are able to compute bids at ad-impression grain, and provide a more relevant CX. If applied across the US Paid Search business (Google only), the OCI performance lift translates to an annualized $2.29B iOPS, $625M net CCP (CCP minus marketing spend). We aim to expand OCI to WW8 by the end of 2025 and anticipate similar performance lifts during this rollout.

#### **How confident are we in US annualized impact of $625M net CCP?**

In Q4 2024, we conducted an A/B test for US Shopping Ads, distributing approximately 50% of the traffic evenly between OCI and the existing bidding system. The A/B test was run on entire portfolio of Shopping Ads. The results showed a performance improvement of 11.68% in iOPS, 9.45% in CCP, and 25.80% in net CCP. Based on these observations, we estimate that the impact amounts to annualized incremental $625M net CCP. The performance gains from OCI have persisted beyond the experiment, and we expect this trend to continue. Like Shopping Ads, early reads from US-Text Ads indicate similar pattern of increased conversion rate driven by OCI. We anticipate that the lifts will increase once we conduct elasticity testing to determine the optimal spending volume that maximizes net CCP.

#### **What are the roll-out plans? **

Given the performance lift, we have two taken two goals for launching OCI:

1. _Retail_: The US-Shopping Ads roll-out is expected to be  completed by the end of Jan-2025, followed by the launch of US-Text Ads by  the end of Apr-2025, after the required 90-day training period. By this  time, the necessary technical infrastructure will also be in place to  support launches in non-US marketplaces. We aim to complete the roll-out  in WW8 by EOY-2025. We are working with EU, JP, MENA, Emerging, Exports  & Secondary Lang teams to finalize the launch timelines for FR, IT,  ES, CA, JP, IN, MX, BR, NL, AE, SA, TR, SE, SG, PL, AU, EG, Exports,  Secondary Lang. (DFD: Feb-2025).
2. _Other_: We are collaborating with Amazon Business, Amazon  Health, and Amazon Music to leverage the existing engineering  infrastructure for launching OCI to support their marketing use cases by  the EOY-2025.

#### **What were some technical challenges that had to be overcome? **

The project faced technical challenges due to external and internal technical integration issues. However, the resolution of these issues led to innovative solutions that brought useful capabilities to the industry at large:

_Chrome launches support for server-to-server calls_: We faced a challenge when Google’s communication about 100% parallel calls for ad clicks turned out to be incorrect, revealing that a large portion of traffic especially from Chrome mobile browser was in direct call mode. This mismatch posed risks to CX due to the intermediate hops that leads to increased latency. Our OCI system is designed for parallel calls to ensure there is low latency and no risk to CX for transiting to Amazon after clicking on advertisement. We convinced Google leadership to support parallel tracking on Chrome browser in April-2024, and to launch server-to-server calls as an alternative, minimizing the CX impact. 

_Manual experimentation setup_: Due to the lack of existing functionality to clone Shopping Ads accounts, we had to manually create the necessary account clones for the OCI experiment. This workaround involved managing complexities, such as ensuring consistency in ASIN portfolios, handling geo-level data, developing robust SOPs for validation, building new data pipelines for reporting. Despite these challenges, a novel experiment design was achieved by using cookie-split randomization and a single account structure, which enhanced the experiment's statistical power. This design allowed for more precise testing while simplifying the account management process, ultimately improving the overall experiment quality.

_Training Times_: After Prime Day, we conducted small-scale testing to validate the Smart Bidding implementation, which revealed that Google's system had technical issues. We escalated these issues, leading to a month-long Google investigation that uncovered a constraint in their systems: conversion signals delayed over 7 days prolonged model training times. This previously unknown limitation prompted Google to update their public documentation and address this constraint in their long term roadmap. To stay on track, we adapted our approach by initiating additional testing in mid-November and implementing new monitoring systems to effectively manage the experiment during the critical Q4 peak period.



